It protects President Trump‚Äôs historic 2017 tax cuts which sparked strong economic growth by fueling job creation and family incomes, increasing the child tax credit, and implementing new tax policies like ‚ÄúNo Tax on Tips‚Äù and ‚ÄúNo Tax on Overtime,‚Äù putting more money back in the pockets of hardworking Americans. This bill also has the heart of America at its core, investing billions into our great agriculture industry to ensure they can keep putting food on our tables. It emphasizes the importance, and dignity, of work by requiring able-bodied Americans to work in order to be eligible for Medicaid and food assistance. And, it also defunds planned parenthood and taxpayer funded transgender surgeries in Medicaid. ¬†   

Over the past week, we have made some real improvements to the bill, and I had hoped that we could rally around eliminating even more waste, fraud and abuse to tackle our mounting national debt as it climbs toward $37 trillion. For example, Medicaid remains weighed down by misplaced priorities and state money-laundering scams. We also did not do enough to shut off the government subsidies to green energy companies.¬†¬†¬† ¬† 

We owe it to our children and grandchildren to build a fiscally responsible future, and the bill could have gone much farther when it comes to getting our spending under control. On balance, however, this package is a win for the American people. But, it‚Äôs also a reminder that Washington still struggles to fully embrace the transformative change we so desperately need. This bill is just the start of our mission to do government differently!

Name: Clyde, Andrew S.
text:
This morning, House Republicans passed President Trump‚Äôs One Big Beautiful Bill with my support.

Over the past few days, I‚Äôve worked tirelessly to improve this legislation, as it‚Äôs critical that we include as many America First priorities as possible. Budget reconciliation provides us a rare, filibuster-proof opportunity to deliver on our promises to the American people ‚Äî including historic tax cuts to hardworking Americans, spending cuts, border security funding, job creation, and massive deregulation.

After productive negotiations with the White House and House GOP Leadership, we moved this legislation in a better direction.¬†

For example, we moved work requirements for able-bodied adults on Medicaid up to December 2026 (from the previous and unserious start in 2029). We also secured new incentives for non-Medicaid expansion states (such as Georgia) and made progress in ending Green New Scam subsidies.

One of my key priorities throughout this process has been restoring our constitutional 2A rights, which have been subjected to unconstitutional infringements for the last 90 years under the draconian NFA. The original bill text only removed the $200 transfer tax for suppressors. Now, the bill eliminates both the transfer and making tax for suppressors, as well as the registration. This is a massive 2A victory ‚Äî one that takes important steps toward restoring our constitutional freedoms.

Unfortunately, the bill does not eliminate the taxation and registration of SBRs, SBSs, and AOWs. Yet we CANNOT give up. Next, this legislation will move to the Senate, providing opportunities for additional positive changes. I‚Äôll be working closely with Senate Republicans to add this provision, and I encourage folks to stay engaged on this matter as the budget reconciliation process moves forward.

Name: Perez, Marie Gluesenkamp
text:
I just cast my vote against a costly and irresponsible budget reconciliation bill.

Washington, D.C. is way out of balance right now, with one party controlling all the levers of government. This massive bill reveals the consequences of single-party control: it doesn‚Äôt balance the federal budget, it doesn‚Äôt balance the competing priorities I hear from my community, and it avoids making tough decisions in favor of making reckless ones.

It‚Äôs a package of party favors for special interests and extremists calling the shots in the majority party right now.
¬†
Politicians love to champion fiscal responsibility and use our national debt as a talking point, but at the end of the day, this wasteful legislation will explode our deficit by $3.8 trillion to advance profound tax cuts for the top 0.1% of earners.¬†
¬†
It drives up costs for everyday Americans on energy, healthcare premiums, and out-of-pocket costs ‚Äì all while gutting the consumer finance watchdog that helps them fight back when they‚Äôre ripped off.
¬†
It breaks the President‚Äôs promise not to touch Medicaid ‚Äì imposing new, difficult-to-navigate red tape and threatening the healthcare of roughly 21,000 people across Southwest Washington.
¬†
It raids food programs that advance our national health, keep food on families‚Äô tables, and support our farmers.
¬†
That‚Äôs the real cost of handing out tax breaks to the wealthiest Americans.
¬†
As some of my House Republican colleagues sounded the alarms about how this bill will balloon our deficit, I stood ready to work with the Majority on a fiscally responsible bill that would level the playing field and make government deliver more effectively. 

Instead, they moved forward on an expensive, partisan plan that failed to include provisions like my bill to close the carried interest loophole ‚Äì a fiscally smart policy advocated for by President Trump.
¬†
Working families understand the bitter consequences of carrying debt, and our federal government needs to meet them in that reality. 

This bill doesn‚Äôt align with the values held by my neighbors and constituents ‚Äì and it disrespects their hard work to make ends meet. 

I‚Äôll keep seeking out bipartisan solutions, fighting to advance opportunity in the middle class, and taking an independent stand for what truly matters to my community.

BREAKING: Rep. Miller Applauds House Passage of President Trump‚Äôs One Big, Beautiful Bill

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

WASHINGTON, D.C. ‚Äî Today, Congresswoman Mary Miller (R-IL) released the following statement after the U.S. House of Representatives passed H.R. 1, the One Big Beautiful Bill Act:

‚ÄúI was proud to cast my vote in support of President Trump‚Äôs One Big, Beautiful Bill,‚Äù said Congresswoman Mary Miller. ‚ÄúThis legislation delivers on the America First agenda that a majority of Americans support. It ensures illegals are stripped of federal SNAP benefits, enforces common-sense work requirements for Medicaid, invests in mass deportation efforts, cuts taxes on tips and overtime, and dismantles Biden‚Äôs radical Green New Deal policies. The House has done its job, now the Senate must act quickly and send this bill to President Trump‚Äôs desk.‚Äù

As a member of the House Agriculture Committee, Rep. Miller successfully secured a key provision in the One Big, Beautiful Bill that prohibits illegal immigrants from receiving taxpayer-funded SNAP benefits. This measure saves billions of dollars and implements a key part of President Trump's agenda.

Name: Smith, Adam
text:
I strongly oppose the Republican budget bill. This bill would balloon the national debt, slash critical services, and deliver nearly $4.6 trillion in tax breaks that overwhelmingly benefit the wealthiest Americans. 

At a time when families are struggling with rising costs, Congress should be strengthening the programs that invest in American communities, not cutting them to pay for permanent tax breaks for billionaires. 

The legislation proposes deep cuts to essential programs that millions of Americans rely on. It slashes health care access for 13.7 million Americans, including children, seniors, and low-income families. It also cuts food assistance from over 42 million people across the country, including essential school lunch programs for hungry children.

These devastating cuts are an attempt to partially offset the revenue losses from massive tax breaks for corporations and ultra-high earners. Under this plan, the top 0.1% of earners‚Äîthose making more than $4 million a year‚Äîwould receive an average tax cut of nearly $390,000 in 2026 alone. Meanwhile, the lowest-income families could see their taxes go up or their benefits cut. This tax policy is unfair and deeply unsustainable. 

Despite these harmful cuts to essential services, the bill still increases the deficit by $3.3 trillion over the next decade, further weakening our fiscal stability just as American families are dealing with higher costs and economic uncertainty. If enacted, this bill would push the national debt to $56.8 trillion by 2034‚Äîor even higher if temporary provisions are extended, as many expect. The legislation also includes a $5.5 trillion increase to the debt ceiling, not to invest in our future, but to finance tax cuts that benefit those who need them the least. 

This is not a serious or responsible budget. It asks working families, veterans, and students to sacrifice, while rewarding the ultra-wealthy with permanent giveaways. I believe we need a budget that protects essential services, invests in opportunity, and restores fiscal integrity‚Äînot one that shifts the burden onto those already struggling to get by. 

I‚Äôll continue to fight for a fairer path forward‚Äîone that puts people first and reflects the values of the communities I serve.

The ugly truth of Donald Trump‚Äôs ‚ÄòBig Beautiful Bill‚Äô is that it strips away healthcare from 20,000 Minnesotans with disabilities, seniors, children, and working parents in Minnesota‚Äôs 4th Congressional District ‚Äì that‚Äôs the equivalent of every resident of Stillwater losing their healthcare overnight. The ugly truth is that 45,000 Minnesotans will go hungry without the SNAP food assistance they rely on ‚Äì the equivalent of every resident of Maplewood going to bed hungry and waking up hungry. The ugly truth is that Donald Trump and his Republican Congressional followers are cutting healthcare and food access for the most vulnerable Minnesotans to give permanent tax breaks to billionaires like Elon Musk and corporations who currently don‚Äôt pay their fair share. In fact, some large corporations pay $0 in taxes. In short, the ugly truth about the ‚ÄòBig Beautiful Bill‚Äô is that it‚Äôs just another Trump GOP Tax Scam.

Under this legislation, the average family earning less than $50,000 would get under $300 in tax cuts in 2027, less than $1 a day, while a wealthy tax filer earning $1,000,000 or more a year would receive about $90,000 in tax breaks. The more the American people learn about this ugly legislation, the more they dislike it, which is why the House Republican majority advanced it through key committees during dead-of-the-night hearings and rushed the floor vote through while most Americans were sleeping.

It was easy to vote no on this bill. Leading with my Minnesota values and representing the voice of my community, I will oppose any Republican efforts to cut Medicaid, Medicare, Social Security, Veterans‚Äô benefits, and nutrition assistance for Minnesota families, especially when they‚Äôre made in service to millionaires and billionaires.

Name: Huizenga, Bill
text:
Today the House passed transformative legislation to deliver permanent tax relief for middle class families and small business job creators.¬†

H.R. 1 prevents the largest tax increase in history while reducing taxes for Americans making $30,000 - $80,000 by 15%.¬†

Additionally, this measure provides relief for seniors while delivering on President Trump‚Äôs promise of no tax on tips as well as no tax on overtime which will help Michiganders keep more of their hard earned money. This bill also makes auto loan interest on a new vehicle tax deductible, a provision that I championed to increase Michigan manufacturing and make buying a new car more affordable.¬†

H.R. 1 ¬†embraces pro-family and pro-parent policies by increasing the Child Tax Credit, enhancing the Adoption Tax Credit, expanding 529 savings accounts, and establishing savings accounts for newborns.¬†

Importantly, H.R. 1 moves to protect and preserve Medicaid for those who need it the most by eliminating waste, fraud, and abuse of this vital program.¬†

This legislation reestablishes work requirements for able-bodied adults without dependents. It stops illegal immigrants from accessing taxpayer funded assistance, cracks down on those enrolled in multiple state programs, and strives to reduce the more than $500 billion in improper payments.

Lastly, H.R. 1 makes critical investments in areas such as border security to ensure the progress made to restore border integrity is not only maintained but enhanced.¬†

Overall, this legislation includes more than $1.5 trillion in deficit reduction, supercharges economic opportunity, and substantially increases take home pay for millions of Americans while setting up Michigan and our nation for a manufacturing renaissance!

Name: Roy, Chip
text:
üö®Rep. Roy¬†Statement on House Passage of The One Big Beautiful Bill Act:

"After much deliberation, I voted yes on H.R. 1, the One Big Beautiful Bill Act. 
 
Months ago, I worked to ensure that any tax cuts or extensions would be connected to an equal or greater amount of spending cuts to force fiscal discipline. The good news is that the bill technically held true to that framework by yielding modest deficit reduction over a 10-year budget window.  Importantly, it does this by cutting spending $1.5 trillion over 10 years, reforming programs like Medicaid and SNAP with work requirements, and improving healthcare freedom by expanding health savings accounts to allow use with Direct Primary Care.
 
But the good things didn‚Äôt just happen by accident. 
 
My fellow budget hawk colleagues and I, including many in the House Freedom Caucus, forced reforms that were critical to making the bill more responsible. We:

 - Accelerated Medicaid work requirements 3 years from 2029 to 2026.

- Helped stave off further Obamacare expansion by aligning State Directed Payments (SDPs) in Medicaid to the rates of Medicare in Medicaid expansion states while allowing states that have not expanded Medicaid (ex., TX) to have SDPs at 110% of Medicare.

- Froze the state provider taxes to ensure states don‚Äôt grow their money laundering schemes.

- Paid Texas and other states back for their border efforts under the Biden administration.

- Began to claw back the ‚ÄúGreen New Scam‚Äù put on steroids by the Inflation Reduction Act‚Äôs (IRA) corrupt subsidies ‚Äì namely by putting in place a required construction start within 60 days of enactment and a much earlier ‚Äúin service‚Äù requirement of 12/31/28 ‚Äì all designed to limit the reach of subsidies.

To be clear, I didn‚Äôt vote for the bill without significant reservations. 
 
For example, in classic Washington fashion, the bill produces sizable deficits in the first 5 years while achieving ‚Äúsavings‚Äù in the future, which means we‚Äôve got to bring forward more savings than I already fought for.
 
And as with most major bills in Washington, this bill was rushed, mashed together, and crammed through the House without sufficient time to review every item carefully. We should do better.
 
The Medicaid money laundering scam was not reformed sufficiently, and far too many of the new green scam subsidies continue to operate.
 
And inexplicably, we funded high-tax state jurisdictions with a $350 billion tax deduction for their ‚ÄúSALT‚Äù tax deductions ‚Äì something I strongly oppose.
 
But even though I supported this bill out of the House, this bill needs massive improvements if we are to make a dent in our deficit or to change the trajectory of this country.  
 
We must reduce deficits much further, even as we continue to work to FULLY repeal the IRA‚Äôs unreliable energy subsidies and reduce the damage done by Obamacare‚Äôs Medicaid expansion.  We can do this most efficiently with state block grants ‚Äì but we can also reduce the 90% FMAP for able bodied people ‚Äì ensuring states are not getting seven times more money for able bodied adults with no children over the most vulnerable in traditional Medicaid ‚Äì and reducing provider taxes to end the unnecessary inflation of costs in healthcare.  
 
I stand ready to work with my colleagues in the Senate to continue to get this bill right before sending it to the President‚Äôs desk."

Name: Calvert, Ken
text:
I promised voters that if they sent me back to Congress, I would fight to keep their taxes low ‚Äì and that‚Äôs exactly what this One Big Beautiful Bill does. The passage of the bill will prevent the looming tax increase that would be the largest in our nation‚Äôs history. Job growth, take-home pay, and economic opportunities hit historic highs following the passage of the 2017 tax cuts. This bill extends and expands those pro-worker and pro-family policies.

To support American workers, the bill eliminates federal income taxes on tips and overtime. To support retirees, the bill includes new tax relief for seniors. To support families, the bill increases the state and local taxes (SALT) deduction cap to $40,000 as well as extends and expands the child tax credit that Republicans doubled in 2017. To support job creators, the bill expands and makes permanent the small business deduction and allows 100% immediate expensing.

The One Big Beautiful Bill includes resources that will allow the Trump Administration to solidify the tremendous progress made in securing our border by completing the southern Border Wall and investing in our Border Patrol. To secure America and support our military, the bill will allow the Defense Department to acquire ships, aircraft, and other essential weapons systems as well as invest in the innovation entities within the Department focused on deploying vital capabilities in a time frame of relevance.

I have made it clear throughout this process that I would not support cuts to Medicaid for seniors, children, mothers, and the disabled. The One Big Beautiful Bill protects these populations and does NOT cut Medicaid for seniors, children, mothers, and the disabled. The bill makes NO changes to Social Security, Medicare, or veterans‚Äô benefits.

The changes to Medicaid strengthen the program by eliminating waste, fraud, and abuse. The bill ensures federal tax dollars are not used to provide Medicaid benefits for illegal immigrants through new immigration status check rules. The bill also implements sensible 20-hour per week work requirements ‚Äì which can be satisfied through either employment, volunteering, or education ‚Äì for able adults without children under 65 years of age. According to the nonpartisan Congressional Budget Office, the only individuals estimated to lose Medicaid benefits because of the bill are illegal immigrants, ineligible recipients who will lose coverage due to better enforcement of eligibility rules, and able adults without children who refuse to satisfy the new work requirements. These are reasonable, responsible Medicaid reforms that protect the most vulnerable as well as taxpayers.

Name: Schneider, Bradley Scott
text:
With several of my Jewish colleagues, I visited the Capital Jewish Museum to pay respects to the two young souls who were brutally, hatefully murdered last night. I thought I'd share with you what I said outside the museum, in response to this horrible, horrible murder:

Last night at this site there was a gathering sponsored by the American Jewish Committee of young professionals, diplomatic professionals, who were dedicating their careers to the idea of building bridges -- bridges between people and bridges between nations.

Jewish tradition going back to Rabbi Hillel‚Äôs famous quotation, ‚ÄúIf I am not for myself, who will be for me? If I am only for myself, what am I?‚Äù -- the idea that we belong together as a nation. Our motto, E Pluribus Unum, from many one. That's the ideal we all believe in and strive for every day in this city.

But there's another reality, a reality that's been true my entire life. As a young child, I remember going to synagogue on high holidays and there would be extra security, there'd be guards. In the 1970s and 80s, those guards started carrying longer guns and in the last number of years those guards have started appearing not just on the high holidays but every single day.

And in the 19 months since October 7th, 2023, we have seen a rise of antisemitism that has been unprecedented in my lifetime, so much so to the point that people are told don't wear outwards display of your faith. Wear a baseball cap instead of a yamaka. Take your Star of David and tuck it in your shirt.

There is a real fear.

So, as we gather here today, we are overwhelming‚Ä¶ overwhelmed by emotions. Emotions of grief at the loss of two beautiful young people who were prepared to make a life together, heading to Israel to become engaged -- to make a promise to each other for a future united.

And [then they had] that future cut short last night.

Instead, their families, rather than gathering under the huppah will be gathering beside a grave saying a Kadesh instead of Seven Blessings.

We have grief. We have fear. But we're not surprised at what happened and we are not going to back down. The resolve of all of us standing here, the resolve of every American Jew, the resolve of Jews around the world is that we will hold on to who we are with pride and defiance. We know our place is in this city, in this country. For us, within the governing halls of the United States.
And we will not let anyone tell us we don't belong.

We are overwhelmed with grief for two beautiful souls, but we must be inspired by their spirit and their example. They were here last night participating in a program about reaching out. That is who they are, that is how they will be remembered.

We're here today to mark their murder, to express our sorrow but we must stand to ensure their memory is always a blessing. We cannot let their death be in vain. We must stand up against hate, against antisemitism, against efforts to divide people and instead make sure we work to unite people.

Name: Collins, Susan M.
text:
The Department of Labor‚Äôs decision to halt enrollment at Maine‚Äôs Loring and Penobscot Job Corps Centers is deeply misguided and will do damage to hundreds of young people. These programs serve nearly 500 Mainers a year and are pillars of support for some of our state‚Äôs most vulnerable teens. Loring alone employs 129 people, making it also one of the largest employers in rural northern Maine.

To show what‚Äôs at stake, today, I shared with the Secretary of Labor the story of Adais Viruet-Torres. When I first met Adais in 2008, she was a Job Corps student at Loring, having escaped a dangerous and unstable life in Connecticut and New York. With training and support from the Loring Job Corps Center, she turned her life around, later earning her nursing degree with honors from Husson in 2019, and continuing on to become a nurse practitioner.

Job Corps works, and it offers so many at-risk young people a real chance at a better life. Eliminating it would rob tens of thousands of students nationwide of the opportunity to gain skills, pursue higher education, join the workforce, and build towards a future they can be proud of‚Äîjust like Adais.

Name: Crenshaw, Dan
text:
Los Chapitos‚Äîa faction of the Sinaloa cartel‚Äîis now aligning with CJNG, their supposed enemy, against the Mayo factions of their own cartel. A lot of these cartel civil wars come down to personal issues and power.

Ivan Guzman, El Chapo‚Äôs son, is now leading the Chapitos after Ovidio Guzman was arrested and extradited to the U.S.

But then, around the same time, 17 of Ovidio‚Äôs relatives crossed the border‚Äîand Ovidio changed his plea to guilty. Obviously there was some kind fo deal being made.

There‚Äôs been long-standing tension between the Chapitos and El Mayo factions of the Sinaloa cartel. The Chapitos live more dangerously. The Mayos are more traditional, calculating. They insulate themselves and stay out of the spotlight.

Here‚Äôs why all this matters: when cartels fight, they become vulnerable. A fractured Sinaloa cartel means an opportunity to strike. The Jalisco cartel is trying to take that opportunity.

Internal dysfunction inside the cartels is good for us, but in the end thr bad guys just move around the chess pieces a bit. To win, we acrually have to take down these groups while they‚Äôre weak and hold that territory.

The good news? We finally have presidents on both sides of the border who take this seriously.

Now we need to back that up ‚Äî by equipping Mexico with the resources, intelligence, and support they need to hit these cartels hard and keep this fight as far from our country as possible.

Name: Schiff, Adam B.
text:
The killing of a young Jewish couple on the streets of Washington last night is nothing short of heartbreaking, and my thoughts are with their families and friends in this time of immense sorrow.

The murder of Yaron and Sarah, reportedly mere weeks before an imminent engagement in the Holy Land, should be a simple and terrible wakeup call for anyone who believes that the rise of antisemitism in America and around the world is not worthy of our concern.

This targeted act of violence, claiming the lives of two young diplomats, should crystallize for all what happens when hate is minimized, normalized, or left unchecked. 

For many months, we have seen an assault on Jews and the Jewish community grow louder and bolder. What began with a terrorist attack against Israel and its people has metastasized into harassment, everyday violence, and this unspeakable tragedy.

To deny the impacts of this disturbing trend only compounds the horror that Jews around the world have felt since October 7.

May Sarah and Yaron‚Äôs memories be a blessing to every member of their family, their friends, and their colleagues both in the Israeli embassy and throughout the Jewish community.

Name: Brecheen, Josh
text:
(2/4) These provisions were a result of liberal ideologies, retained by some in the Republican House of Representatives, who allowed these to remain in the One Big Beautiful Bill prior to it coming to our committee. These ideologies are NOT in line with the mandate President Trump was given by the American people, and he was NOT the one who put them in the bill.¬†

My colleagues and I worked through the weekend, negotiating with House leadership and the White House to fix these flaws. When the revised framework came up on the evening of Sunday, May 18th, I voted ‚Äúpresent‚Äù‚Äînot to dodge responsibility, but to honor the progress made while signaling that more work was needed. This was the first time I‚Äôve ever voted present, and I did not do so lightly. I wanted to recognize the headway we had made in negotiations with the White House and the Speaker, relative to wind and solar tax credit reform and work requirements.

I believe in the Scripture in Matthew 5:37 which says, ‚ÄúLet your yes be yes, and your no be no.‚Äù In this situation, I couldn‚Äôt be a ‚Äúyes,‚Äù because there were still things that had to be negotiated relative to the math working out, like SALT from the New Yorkers‚Äô request and a hanging CBO score on the unintended consequences of Medicaid expansion.

I didn‚Äôt want to vote ‚Äúno,‚Äù either, because it would kill the bill. So the four of us voted ‚Äúpresent,‚Äù knowing it would allow the bill to move forward, with Leadership fully knowing we would continue negotiations so that I could get to a ‚Äúyes‚Äù vote on the floor. This was fully explained to Leadership and the White House and we all agreed to do this before the present vote was cast.

After days of working with President Trump and the White House team, Speaker Mike Johnson, and other members of House Leadership, we made significant steps to move this legislation more in line with President Trump‚Äôs agenda so that we have the tools we need to keep his promises to the American people.¬†

Name: Brecheen, Josh
text:
‚úçüèºüßµ(1/4) Why I Voted Yes on the One Big Beautiful Bill 

Writing to Henry Knox in 1795 as he faced the intense national debate over the Jay Treaty, George Washington described his lack of perfect wisdom: ‚ÄúI have found no better guide hitherto than upright intentions, and close investigation.‚Äù Not claiming to be an infallible man, Washington relied upon his honest convictions and a close examination of the facts to guide him through difficult decisions.¬†

The cornerstone of upright intentions is truth.

Oklahomans rightly expect their representatives to embody upright intentions, be guided by the truth, and diligently represent them. That‚Äôs why, after a week of tough negotiations, I changed my vote on the One Big Beautiful Bill‚Äîin good conscience first voting ‚Äúno‚Äù in committee, then ‚Äúpresent‚Äù in committee to allow it to pass, and finally a ‚Äúyes‚Äù on the floor after the bill was improved. I want you to know why.

When the bill first came before the House Budget Committee on May 16th, I closely examined the text as drafted by other House members, and found it didn‚Äôt deliver on several key conservative promises in keeping with President Trump‚Äôs commitments on ending the Green New Scam and meeting our Budget Committee blueprint for fiscal discipline.

After consulting @AlexEpstein‚Äîauthor of the book Fossil Future‚Äîand other energy experts, it was apparent that the bill failed to do a true repeal of the Green New Scam‚Äôs wind and solar tax credits. Instead of terminating these subsidies this Congress, the bill relied on future Congresses to adhere to ‚Äúphaseouts‚Äù starting in 2029. The promise to start phasing out wind and solar subsidies after President Trump‚Äôs term ended was a recipe for lobbyists to circumnavigate him.¬†¬†¬†

Energy security is national security, and my conservative colleagues and I were deeply concerned that the bill did not provide a pathway to end solar and wind subsidies that prop up Chinese industries at the expense of Oklahoma‚Äôs oil and gas jobs. Oklahoma is America‚Äôs 5th largest natural gas producer, and our nation‚Äôs economy depends on energy independence‚Äînot reliance on China. Currently, China dominates the global solar supply chain and is subsidized by American dollars, as solar accounts for 61% of all new electricity generated in the United States in the last few years.

Even worse, if these subsidies are allowed to continue, we risk our electric grid becoming entirely dependent on subsidized, unreliable energy that is linked to communist China‚Äîmaking our grid vulnerable to CCP attacks. As reported nationally this week, Chinese tech is being found embedded in solar components connected to our grid.¬†

Since 1999, there have been at least ten times that Congress has promised to end the type of tax subsidies that wind and solar now enjoy, yet each time, they‚Äôve kicked the can down the road (see below chart). In order to ensure these tax credits end, it was vital that the timeline be kept within President Trump‚Äôs term‚Äîwhere he would ensure the Green New Scam would end and not let lobbyists overpower Republican promises to do so.¬†

As Patrick Henry said, "I have but one lamp by which my feet are guided, and that is the lamp of experience.‚Äù Experience would tell us‚Äîas history often repeats itself‚Äîthat Congress will delay on this promise yet again without President Trump to hold them accountable. I could not advance a bill that enabled this in good conscience.¬†

I was also gravely concerned by the lack of meaningful Medicaid reform in the bill. The old bill delayed work requirements for able-bodied citizens until 2029‚Äîa timeline that did a disservice to millions of hardworking Americans. Our no vote in committee was to address the things we knew did not align with conservative principles. (cont.)

Name: Brecheen, Josh
text:
(3/4) The final bill obtains a true repeal of Green New Scam wind and solar subsidies for new projects starting 60 days after the bill is signed into law. It moves Medicaid work requirements up to 2026, restoring the dignity of work in America. And it prohibits taxpayer funds via Medicaid paying for transgender surgeries for adults.¬†

And again, the math works now‚Äîin keeping with our Budget Committee‚Äôs blueprint regarding CBO scores on savings in tandem with growth expectations as tied to President Trump‚Äôs first term. These important revisions clarified my decision to finally support the bill and were in line with what I know is truthful, of both my convictions and yours. I was able to have upright intentions after close examination.¬†

In addition to all these other things we‚Äôve worked on, some additional victories in the bill include:

‚Ä¢ Preventing a 24% tax hike on the average eastern Oklahoman;¬†
‚Ä¢ Investing a historic $81 billion in Border Security to build the wall, increase the number of border patrol agents, and acquire technologies to prevent the flow of illicit drugs like fentanyl into our country;¬†
‚Ä¢ Including the REINS Act, which prevents bureaucrats from issuing costly rules that will increase inflation and harm our economy (which I had the honor of adding to the bill in the Budget Committee);¬†
‚Ä¢ Removing suppressors from the National Firearm Registry, restoring the right of law-abiding Americans to bear arms;¬†
‚Ä¢ Providing tax relief for our great seniors;¬†
‚Ä¢ Implementing a tax on remittances to ensure money earned in the United States goes to supporting American businesses and communities;¬†
‚Ä¢ Expediting permitting to promote American energy dominance;¬†
‚Ä¢ Requiring an accelerated audit of the Department of Defense¬†

In my discussions with the Budget Committee, their score‚Äîbased upon the work of @chiproytx, @RepRalphNorman, @Rep_Clyde, and myself to negotiate these changes‚Äîwould save between $100-130 billion dollars in savings over the next 10 years. Additionally, we also legitimized the previous savings that the CBO had scored relative to ending the Green New Scam, whereas before it was calculated on what was never going to happen, based on history.¬†

The final product is not complete as this bill now heads to the Senate. My hope is that all the good we did will hold solid moving forward. I stayed prayerful throughout this entire process, analyzing motives and truth.¬†

I want to thank President @realDonaldTrump and his team and @SpeakerJohnson for giving us the runway to strengthen conservative commitments in the One Big Beautiful Bill. And I am even more grateful for your trust as I continue to represent your values and, to the best of my ability, uphold the convictions we as Oklahomans hold dear.

Name: Brecheen, Josh
text:
(2/4) These provisions were a result of liberal ideologies, retained by some in the Republican House of Representatives, who allowed these to remain in the One Big Beautiful Bill prior to it coming to our committee. These ideologies are NOT in line with the mandate President Trump was given by the American people, and he was NOT the one who put them in the bill.¬†

My colleagues and I worked through the weekend, negotiating with House leadership and the White House to fix these flaws. When the revised framework came up on the evening of Sunday, May 18th, I voted ‚Äúpresent‚Äù‚Äînot to dodge responsibility, but to honor the progress made while signaling that more work was needed. This was the first time I‚Äôve ever voted present, and I did not do so lightly. I wanted to recognize the headway we had made in negotiations with the White House and the Speaker, relative to wind and solar tax credit reform and work requirements.

I believe in the Scripture in Matthew 5:37 which says, ‚ÄúLet your yes be yes, and your no be no.‚Äù In this situation, I couldn‚Äôt be a ‚Äúyes,‚Äù because there were still things that had to be negotiated relative to the math working out, like SALT from the New Yorkers‚Äô request and a hanging CBO score on the unintended consequences of Medicaid expansion.

I didn‚Äôt want to vote ‚Äúno,‚Äù either, because it would kill the bill. So the four of us voted ‚Äúpresent,‚Äù knowing it would allow the bill to move forward, with Leadership fully knowing we would continue negotiations so that I could get to a ‚Äúyes‚Äù vote on the floor. This was fully explained to Leadership and the White House and we all agreed to do this before the present vote was cast.

After days of working with President Trump and the White House team, Speaker Mike Johnson, and other members of House Leadership, we made significant steps to move this legislation more in line with President Trump‚Äôs agenda so that we have the tools we need to keep his promises to the American people.¬†

On Monday afternoon, May 19th, I learned that transgender surgeries for adults as paid for by Medicaid was another problem that needed to be addressed in the bill. I brought this up to the Speaker Monday evening, and based on his response, it was the first he had heard of it remaining a part of the bill. I then began working with him to remove this, letting him know it was an issue for me when it went to the floor.¬†

Over the next couple of days, between discussions with the White House and the Speaker, we got all of this ironed out. The numbers worked out‚Äîin keeping with our budget blueprint to ensure deficit neutrality, so that we could operate in truth‚Äîand I got to a ‚ÄúYES.‚Äù (cont.)

Name: Houlahan, Chrissy
text:
Law(less) + (Dis)Order(ly) Episode 15:

None of these actions make our country safer or citizens more prosperous, but here are some of the things the Trump Administration delivered this week:

President Trump has now officially accepted a $400 million plane from the royal family of Qatar with zero oversight from Congress because Speaker Mike Johnson refuses to go against the President.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we celebrate individuals across our district whose acts of selflessness and generosity inspire us all. As we approach Memorial Day, we‚Äôre proud to highlight a young leader whose actions remind us that honoring those who‚Äôve served our nation should never be limited to just one day‚Äîit‚Äôs something we must carry forward every day through how we live and how we give back. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero: 16-year-old Ryan Lovenstein of Southampton.
 
Ryan, a sophomore at William Tennent High School, grew up next door to Joseph Martines, a proud World War II Army Air Force veteran and beloved member of our community. Their friendship grew naturally‚Äîfrom front porch conversations and Phillies games on the radio to a shared respect that spanned generations. Through Joe, Ryan gained firsthand insight into true character, patriotism, and service.
 
When Joe passed away in 2023 at the age of 98, Ryan felt moved to ensure Joe‚Äôs legacy lived on. He built the Joseph Martines Memorial Field, a wiffleball field in his own backyard, complete with a custom scoreboard bearing Joe‚Äôs name. Quickly, the field became a community gathering place, uniting neighbors, teammates, and friends in the spirit of remembrance, friendship, and patriotism.
 
Yet Ryan‚Äôs efforts didn‚Äôt stop there.
 
Last weekend, Ryan expanded his vision, hosting the first annual Wiffle Ball for the Wounded tournament at Tamanend Park. Rallying local businesses, volunteers, and community members, Ryan raised nearly $2,000 for the @TMFoundation, an organization dedicated to supporting veterans and families of fallen service members. What began as a tribute to a single veteran has blossomed into something greater‚Äîa community movement inspired by gratitude, kindness, and service.
 
Ryan‚Äôs example reminds us that truly honoring our veterans goes beyond reflection‚Äîit requires action. He has shown us that patriotism is best expressed not through occasional gestures but through meaningful acts of kindness, service, and community spirit.
 
To Ryan‚Äîthank you for honoring our heroes. Join me in applauding this extraordinary young leader‚Äîhis future is bright, and thanks to him, the legacy of one American hero now lives on in a way that brings people together and lifts us all.

Name: McCormick, David
text:
I applaud @realDonaldTrump , Secretary Bessent, and other senior administration officials in achieving this huge victory for America and the U.S. Steel Corporation.¬†
¬†
Only Donald Trump could have made this happen and I‚Äôm grateful to him for having me, Congressman Mike Kelly (PA-16), and Congressman Dan Meuser (PA-09) from our Pennsylvania delegation in the Oval Office yesterday to discuss it. I told him what I have said all along. My priorities are preserving and expanding jobs and investment in the Mon Valley. This partnership gets it done.¬†
¬†
This $14 billion investment by Nippon Steel ensures this storied American company remains under US leadership, dramatically enhances US domestic steel production capacity, protects more than 11,000 Pennsylvania jobs, and supports the creation of at least 14,000 more. I have made clear my top priority in any agreement is protecting the jobs of workers in the Mon Valley, in addition to securing renewed investment in Pennsylvania steel jobs and the local economy, while ensuring that U.S. Steel remains under US control.¬†This partnership is great for the economy, great for national security, and great for the hardworking people of Pennsylvania. I am proud to stand by President Trump as he lives up to our shared promise to rebuild US manufacturing and deliver for America‚Äôs workers.

Name: Mrvan, Frank J.
text:
From the very beginning of this proposed acquisition, I was steadfast in voicing serious concerns about the implications of foreign ownership ‚Äì particularly Nippon Steel‚Äôs record on trade practices ‚Äì and the critical importance of preserving American control over our steel production, which is vital to our national security.

In the months since, as the Vice Chairman of the Congressional Steel Caucus, I‚Äôve listened closely to the many voices raised across the political spectrum, including from the prior administration and the Trump Administration.  It is clear that this unified front of concern and advocacy played a crucial role in shaping the terms, incentives, and safeguards now in place.

Thanks to this persistent and bipartisan pressure, we are in a stronger, more secure position today than we were at the time of the initial announcement.  But let me be clear: this is not the end of our oversight.  Nippon Steel must be held to every promise made ‚Äì from promises to the hardworking steelworkers of Northwest Indiana and the City of Gary, to the economic and strategic interests of the United States.  We will not hesitate to act if those commitments are broken.

Name: Meuser, Daniel
text:
In their efforts to oppose commonsense reforms to strengthen Medicaid and ensure its sustainability for the most vulnerable and future Americans, Democrats are once again resorting to fear mongering‚Äînot facts.

Below is a breakdown of common Democratic myths and the real facts about the Big Beautiful Bill (BBB) Medicaid provisions:

‚∏ª

DEMOCRAT FEAR MONGERING:

Millions will lose access to Medicaid under cruel new work requirements.

FACT:
The BBB‚Äôs Medicaid community engagement provisions apply only to able-bodied adults without dependents‚Äînot to seniors, people with disabilities, pregnant women, or caregivers.
Beginning January 1, 2026, these adults can meet the requirement by working, volunteering, attending school, or participating in job training for at least 80 hours a month.

This is not punitive‚Äîit‚Äôs empowering. It recognizes that Medicaid should support not just health but upward mobility and personal responsibility.

‚∏ª

DEMOCRAT FEAR MONGERING:

Medicaid recipients will be kicked off the program due to paperwork errors and red tape.

FACT:
The BBB combats fraud, waste, and abuse, not eligible recipients.
For example, it ends the ‚Äúgood faith‚Äù waiver by 2030, ensuring states can no longer dodge accountability for improper payments to ineligible individuals or providers.

It uses the SSA Death Master File to prevent payments to deceased individuals and creates a federal system to prevent dual-state enrollment.

Verifying eligibility is not ‚Äúred tape‚Äù‚Äîit‚Äôs responsible governance.

‚∏ª

DEMOCRAT FEAR MONGERING:

The bill targets immigrants and punishes those in need.

FACT:
Federal law has long required that Medicaid recipients be citizens or legal residents.

The BBB strengthens enforcement by ending federal funding during the 90-day verification period for those without verified status.

No funding will go to those who are ineligible under federal law‚Äîthis includes approximately 1.4 million illegal immigrants and 1.2 million other ineligible individuals who are currently on the rolls. 

‚∏ª

DEMOCRAT FEAR MONGERING:

States will be penalized for trying to provide compassionate care.

FACT:
Beginning in 2028, states that deliberately fund health care for undocumented immigrants through Medicaid-like programs will face a 10% reduction in federal Medicaid matching funds.

This ensures that Medicaid remains focused on U.S. citizens and legal residents‚Äîthe populations it was designed to serve.

‚∏ª

DEMOCRAT FEAR MONGERING:

These changes are meant to slash Medicaid and gut funding.

FACT:
The BBB doesn‚Äôt slash Medicaid‚Äîit strengthens it.

By removing ineligible individuals and focusing resources on those truly in need, the reforms ensure long-term sustainability of the program.

Medicaid spending is projected to grow under the BBB, not shrink, because the focus is on integrity and efficiency‚Äînot cuts.

‚∏ª

Bottom Line:
The BBB reforms don‚Äôt weaken Medicaid‚Äîthey preserve it for those who need it most: vulnerable seniors, low-income children, people with disabilities, and legal working families.

Democrats are trying to protect bureaucracy. Republicans are fighting to protect people.

Name: Smith, Tina
text:
On this 5th anniversary of George Floyd‚Äôs murder, I‚Äôve been remembering the anguish, trauma, and moral outrage of my Minnesota community. Since that terrible day there have been important victories and progress made, but also terrible losses and retreats.¬†George Floyd‚Äôs killer is paying the price for his crimes, and nothing Donald Trump can do will change that. The Minneapolis Police Department and my city will continue to make slow but meaningful steps toward reform and systemic change. Donald Trump‚Äôs Justice Department has abandoned the Consent Decree, but we will not. Congress has failed so far to pass the George Floyd Justice in Policing Act, but local communities like mine have banned no-knock warrants and the use of choke holds.
¬†
It is also true that across our nation the number of police killings continues to go up, and the people who are dying are much more likely to be Native, Black and Latino people. Only a fool would look at how Donald Trump lifted up White Afrikaners as the victims of genocide and see anything but the race baiting and racism that it is. Big corporations that embraced Black businesses and a more diverse workforce only a year ago have erased those efforts as they shamefully kowtow to Trump and MAGA. So, there have been retreats and losses also.
¬†
James Baldwin said, ‚Äúnot everything that is faced can be changed, but nothing can be changed unless it is faced.‚Äù Today, I‚Äôm inspired by the strength of the young leaders I see here in Minnesota who refuse to give in, give up or forget. I‚Äôm with them.

Here in our PA-1 community, we walk the same ground where liberty was fought for and won. Today at @WashXingPark, I joined neighbors to honor the soldiers who gave their lives here in December 1776. These were ordinary citizens who answered an extraordinary call‚Äîmarching through snow and uncertainty to secure the promise of freedom. Their courage turned the tide of history and helped lay the foundation for the nation we cherish today.

As we commemorate Memorial Day Weekend, we do so with deep gratitude for the generations of heroes from our community and across the country who gave everything to defend our freedoms and way of life.

Thank you to Col. Jeffrey R. McGeary of Doylestown and U.S. Army Major Spencer G. Garrison of Yardley for your service and for helping lead today‚Äôs tribute‚Äîand to Executive Director Jennifer Martin and the entire WCHP team for preserving this sacred piece of our national story.

Join me in wishing Evelyn a very Happy 90th birthday‚Äîshe‚Äôs an inspiration to us all!

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Today I had the honor of joining veterans, families, and community leaders at VFW Post 8397 in San Antonio, now renamed in tribute to Lance Corporal David Lee Espinosa.

I thank the family of Lance Corporal Espinosa for their presence, their strength, and the sacrifice they continue to carry with such grace. I also want to thank Commander Charleen G. Hernandez and every member of Post 8397 for their hospitality, their leadership, and their unwavering dedication to remembrance. To every veteran that was in attendance, to the families, and to every guest who came to honor our fallen, thank you.

Lance Corporal David Lee Espinosa was born in Laredo, raised in Rio Bravo, graduated from LBJ High School, and like so many who wear our nation‚Äôs uniform, he believed in something larger than himself. He believed in service. In sacrifice. In standing up when others stand back.

The renaming of this post is more than a tribute. It is a promise to remember his legacy and uphold the values he lived and died for.

May God bless Lance Corporal David Lee Espinosa and may God continue to bless the United States of America.

text:
Staff Sergeant Gene A. Vance of Morgantown, West Virginia

KIA: May 19, 2002 - Paktika Province, Afghanistan

A member of the Special Forces, Sgt. Vance was on patrol with American and Afghan comrades when they were ambushed by Taliban fighters. Vance was critically wounded by enemy rifle fire, and despite his wounds, he continued to translate intelligence for Afghan forces in the area, likely saving many lives.

Sergeant Vance was the first member of the National Guard killed in action since Vietnam, and he was the first West Virginian killed during the Global War on Terror.

Name: Moore, Riley M.
text:
Corporal Thomas W. Bennett of Morgantown, West Virginia

KIA: February 11, 1969 - Chu Pa Region, Vietnam

Cpl. Bennett was killed while courageously attempting to save the life of one of his comrades while under intense fire. Bennett, a devout Christian and conscientious objector, served as a combat medic who would repeatedly brave enemy fire in order to provide life-saving aid and carry his wounded comrades to safety.

He was the second conscientious objector in US history to receive the Medal of Honor, and was the only conscientious objector to receive the Medal of Honor during the Vietnam War.

Name: Moore, Riley M.
text:
Private First Class Ralph E. Pomeroy of Quinwood, West Virginia

KIA: October 15, 1952 - Kangwon Province, Korea

Pfc. Pomeroy was killed while manning a machine gun to protect his platoon's flank. When the enemy attacked, he immediately opened fire on the advancing troops, inflicting a heavy toll in casualties and blunting the assault. The enemy attempted to neutralize his gun, and despite suffering severe wounds and seeing his gun mount destroyed by mortar fire, he took the heavy weapon in his arms and continued to rake the attackers.

When his ammunition was expended he used his machine gun as a club and was mortally wounded in hand-to-hand combat. His actions maintained the integrity of his platoon's perimeter and contained the enemy attack. Pfc. Pomeroy was posthumously awarded the Medal of Honor.

Pomeroy was featured in Conor Timmis's Korean War documentary "Finnigan's War."

T/Sgt. Hendreck was mortally wounded while leading an assault in the town of Lembeck. Name: Moore, Riley M.
text:
Staff Sergeant J. Edward Kelley of Keyser, West Virginia

KIA: January 31, 1945 - Kesternich, Germany

S/Sgt. Kelley was killed charging a machine gun nest which he was able to incapacitate before he died. Kelley had sustained wounds the day before but did not seek medical attention, and instead he rushed into danger at every opportunity in order to make a path for his squad, clearing houses and taking out snipers and machine guns single handedly. His aggression and courage inspired his men to seize the village of Kesternich. S/Sgt. Kelley was posthumously awarded the Medal of Honor.

The J. Edward Kelley Society offers an annual award to exceptional athletes from his alma mater, Keyser High School.

Name: Moore, Riley M.
text:
Sergeant Herbert J. Thomas of South Charleston, West Virginia

KIA: November 7, 1943 - Bougainville, Solomon Islands

A recipient of the Medal of Honor, Sgt. Thomas was killed in action by enemy Japanese forces during the Battle of Koromokina Lagoon. Sgt. Thomas and his group had fearlessly pressed forward against Japanese machine guns in dense jungle, taking out two enemy crews with rifle fire and grenades. Thomas threw a grenade at a third machine gun which unfortunately struck jungle vines and fell back into his group of Marines. Sgt. Thomas deliberately flung himself upon the grenade to smother the explosion. Inspired by his selfless action, his men charged the enemy machine gun and killed the crew.

In 1945, a U.S. Navy destroyer was commissioned in his honor.

text:
As we gather with family and friends this Memorial Day, we pause to honor the brave men and women who made the ultimate sacrifice for our nation‚Äôs freedom. Representing New York‚Äôs 21st Congressional District, the cradle of the American Revolution, is a profound honor. From the hallowed grounds of Saratoga and Ticonderoga to the modern-day heroes of Fort Drum and the 10th Mountain Division‚Äîthe most deployed division in the U.S. Army since 9/11‚Äîservice and sacrifice are woven into the very fabric of our region.

The 10th Mountain Division‚Äôs storied legacy, from the battlefields of World War II to conflicts in Afghanistan, Iraq, and beyond, reflects the enduring courage of our soldiers. This Memorial Day, my thoughts are with the Gold Star families and all those who have lost loved ones in service to our country. Their sacrifices are forever etched in our nation‚Äôs history, and we owe them an eternal debt of gratitude. As the chief advocate for Fort Drum in Congress, I remain steadfast in ensuring our soldiers and their families have the resources, support, and recognition they deserve.

Let us reflect on the profound cost of our freedom and renew our pledge to support our veterans, active-duty service members, and military families. In a region where patriotism runs deep, we are reminded that America remains the land of the free because of the brave. May God bless our fallen heroes, their families, and the United States of America.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Today, across our community, we came together to honor the generations of brave Americans from our community who gave their lives so we could live free.

From Langhorne to Washington Crossing to Croydon, these Memorial Day ceremonies reminded us that freedom is never free‚Äîit is earned through sacrifice, paid for with courage, and preserved through remembrance.

I‚Äôm deeply grateful to the Jesse W. Soby American Legion, the Guardians of the National Cemetery, VFW Post 1597, and the many volunteers and organizations who made every tribute possible and work to ensure our fallen heroes and their families are never forgotten.

Among those we honored today was U.S. Army Staff Sergeant Jae Moon, a Neshaminy graduate who was killed in Iraq in 2006 at just 21 years old. Standing with his family at Washington Crossing National Cemetery, we honored his life and reaffirmed our enduring promise: that his sacrifice‚Äîand the sacrifices of all who served and fell‚Äîwill forever be remembered.

What moved me most today was seeing so many young people taking part‚Äîstanding in respect and learning what it means to serve. Patriotism isn‚Äôt inherited‚Äîit‚Äôs taught, lived, and passed down.

This day calls on each of us not only to remember‚Äîbut to live lives worthy of their sacrifice.

May God bless all our fallen heroes and Gold Star families‚Äîand may He continue to bless the United States of America.

Name: Waters, Maxine
text: Today, as I memorialize the loss of so many of our men and women who paid the ultimate sacrifice for serving our nation, I am also mourning the loss of my dear friend and colleague, Congressman Charlie Rangel. Congressman Rangel has passed, but he left a legacy of service and commitment to this country for us all to try to emulate. Congressman Rangel excelled in his service in the United States Army, he was a dedicated veteran who was awarded the Purple Heart and the Bronze Star with valor. He was a co-founder of the Congressional Black Caucus. He was a prolific legislator who fought not only for civil rights but for veterans, healthcare, education, and organized labor. I worked closely with Congressman Rangel as we worked to eliminate apartheid in South Africa. He left a record of leadership to be recorded in history. My friend retired in 2017, and I‚Äôve missed him every day since then. I will honor him & his legacy of service by supporting all of the causes that he led in the US House of Representatives. Farewell, my dear friend. God bless you and all the loved ones you leave behind.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Today, I had the profound honor of joining veterans, families, and community leaders at Fort Sam Houston National Cemetery, a sacred place that reminded us not just of the cost of freedom but of the courage that defends it. I also had the privilege of speaking at the ceremony, where we came together in reflection, remembrance, and recommitment.

I‚Äôd like to recognize the extraordinary team who care for these hallowed grounds with such dignity and compassion: Director Jerry Lefler, Assistant Director Graham Wright, and every dedicated staff member who ensures that every hero laid to rest there is honored with the respect they deserve. Thank you as well to Julianne Flynn, Executive Director of VA South Texas Health Care, and John Mendoza, Deputy Medical Center Director of VA South Texas Health Care, for your leadership and steadfast support of our veterans and their families.

To the veterans who joined us, to the Gold Star families whose strength humbles us all, and to the men and women of the Department of Veterans Affairs, your presence was a powerful tribute to those we came to remember. Your continued service and sacrifice speak volumes.

On this Memorial Day, communities across the country paused to reflect. But there, among the headstones, we did more than remember. We honored. We recommitted ourselves to the values these men and women lived and died for.

Fort Sam Houston National Cemetery stands as more than a final resting place. It is a powerful testament to the legacy of those who served our nation with courage and conviction. Each grave told a story of someone who believed in something greater than themselves.

As a proud Texan and member of Congress, I was reminded once again how deeply service is woven into the fabric of our state. In San Antonio, Military City USA, service is not just a tradition. It is a way of life.

To the families of the fallen, your quiet strength and grace reminded us all what it means to carry the weight of loss with dignity. Your sacrifice will never be forgotten. We must ensure that the values these heroes defended remain at the heart of our nation.

May God bless our veterans, their families, and all those who serve. And may God forever bless the United States of America.

This morning I wanted to tell you something you probably don‚Äôt hear enough of on Memorial Day: the story of the Gold Star wife. This morning I had the honor to speak at the Forest Park Cemetery, where many of our service members are laid to rest. It was amazing to see so many people there, taking this day to remember and memorialize the fallen. Volunteers got up early and placed flowers by every grave. Many Gold Star familes were in attendance, and my words were meant for them directly. This is the story of the Gold Star wife. It‚Äôs something I wrote a few years ago, a semi-fictional story based on the many experiences I‚Äôve had with Gold Star Widows, many of them close friends to this day. They are some of the strongest women I‚Äôve ever had the honor of knowing. It was hard to read it without getting a little emotional, to be honest.

Never Forget.

Name: Mullin, Markwayne
text:
üö® UPDATE: President Trump‚Äôs ‚ÄòOne Big Beautiful Bill.'

We've gotten a ton of questions on what's NEXT. Here's a breakdown:

This week, @SenateGOP will begin to "scrub" the 1,000+ page bill to comply with something called the Byrd rule. 

I‚Äôve called it the ‚ÄúByrd Bath.‚Äù 

In short: because reconciliation (this bill) is a fast-track process that only requires 51 Senate votes versus 60, there are strict rules for compliance. The bill must directly impact federal spending or taxes.

For example, liberals previously tried to use their own reconciliation process to give mass amnesty to illegal aliens, but they FAILED (aka, it didn't pass the Byrd rule) because it would've been a huge policy change that outweighed budget impact.

Note: The House is NOT bound by the Byrd rule‚Äîonly we are. I've used this example: the House has to fit through a garage door, the Senate has to squeeze through a window in the garage door. 

It just comes down to process. We‚Äôve got one shot to get it right. President Trump knows about the Byrd rule, and we're in 24/7 communication to PASS THE BILL and DELIVER.

Name: Bell, Wesley
text:
Ralph Goldsticker Jr. passed this week at 103. A son of St. Louis, he flew missions over Europe in WWII, served again in Korea, and came home to raise a family, build a career, and give back every chance he got.

Even in his 90s and 100s, Ralph was still serving. Talking to students. Volunteering at hospitals. Flying to France at 102 to honor his fallen brothers. He even gave the President a little advice while he was there.
He didn‚Äôt chase attention. He just showed up‚Äîfor his country, his family, and his city.

There aren‚Äôt many WWII veterans left. These men are real heroes‚Äîand as their numbers dwindle, it‚Äôs on us to make sure their stories, their sacrifices, and what they fought for aren‚Äôt forgotten.

St. Louis is fortunate to call him one of our own. May his memory be a blessing.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(5/13) SCOTUS held in 1978‚Äîand again in 2023‚Äîthat universities cannot use racial quotas in their admissions decisions, yet many universities still ignore the law.

American taxpayers provide more than $28B to medical schools, and they expect these universities to follow the law.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(4/13) UCLA isn‚Äôt alone. Harvard Medical School reportedly set exact percentages of minority and female faculty to hire‚Äî89% for women and 34% from minority groups that Harvard deemed worthy.

These quotas are immoral. They‚Äôre also illegal.

https://t.co/HuzAeSDNHu

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(3/13) Since adopting an ‚Äúanti-racism roadmap‚Äù in 2020, UCLA's medical school ranking has plummeted.

More than half of the students failed their standardized exams on emergency medicine, family medicine, internal medicine, and pediatrics‚Äîa failure rate 10X the national average.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(7/13) The EDUCATE Act would strip federal funding from any university that denies qualified students admission because of their race or sex.

Medical degrees aren‚Äôt participation prizes, and fair-minded Americans don‚Äôt want to fund universities that treat them as such.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(6/13) Congress doesn‚Äôt need to sit on the sidelines while a generation of medical students fights this issue in the courts.

We‚Äôre introducing the EDUCATE Act to ensure that American tax dollars aren‚Äôt used to poison the next generation of doctors with DEI.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(9/13) The EDUCATE Act would also prohibit universities from compelling their students to complete DEI coursework.

No patient wants a doctor who spent more time debating whether a mother should be called a ‚Äúbirthing person‚Äù than they did in a science lab.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(8/13) Our bill would also prevent universities from forcing students to take an oath to support a university‚Äôs definition of diversity.

No school should force students to pledge allegiance to ‚Äúsocial justice‚Äù instead of patient well-being.

https://t.co/e6Dlg3yTQF

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(10/13) Finally, we must eliminate DEI offices that are fueling the obsession with race and gender in America‚Äôs medical schools.

The sole purpose of DEI departments is to find new ways to skirt our laws on racial and gender quotas, and American taxpayers are done paying for it.

Name: Kennedy, John
text:
(12/13) It‚Äôs wrong for universities, which are supported by American taxpayers, to prioritize the DEI agenda over merit in any academic program, but it‚Äôs lethal to do this in medical schools. It needs to stop.

There is no reward for being stupid.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
This morning in Laredo, I had the privilege of honoring two pillars of our community during a special recognition ceremony. One was for a lifetime of public service and the other for preserving the legacy of our shared history.

First, I recognized Mayor Dr. Victor D. Trevi√±o for his decades of unwavering service to the people of Laredo. From his roots at Nixon High School to his leadership as our City Health Authority during the COVID-19 pandemic, Mayor Trevi√±o has always led with compassion, humility, and purpose. His efforts, including a binational vaccination campaign that administered nearly 300,000 vaccines, saved lives and brought communities together in a time of crisis. Today, I proudly presented him with a Congressional Record entry to honor his lifelong dedication to public health and service.

I also had the honor of recognizing the Order of Granaderos y Damas de G√°lvez as they celebrate 50 years of preserving and promoting the vital but often overlooked role Spain played in the American Revolution. From their beginnings in San Antonio to the continued work of the Laredo Chapter, their mission is clear: to ensure that figures like General Bernardo de G√°lvez are remembered for their courageous contributions to our nation‚Äôs founding. Their efforts earned them a well-deserved entry into the Congressional Record as well.

This ceremony was a meaningful acknowledgment of the individuals and organizations whose work strengthens our community, whether through public service or the preservation of history. Their contributions remind us of the value of leadership, dedication, and a deeper understanding of where we come from.

text:
Across our district, we‚Äôre fortunate to have some of the most forward-thinking schools and exceptional educators in the nation‚Äîand Palisades School District is a standout example.

From the student-run Pirates Pier Caf√© and state-of-the-art Science and Robotics Center to their TV studio and district-wide STEAM initiatives, Palisades is doing more than educating‚Äîthey‚Äôre empowering the next generation of leaders, innovators, and problem-solvers.

But today‚Äôs visit wasn‚Äôt just about seeing these impressive programs in action‚Äîit was about listening. I heard directly from educators and administrators about what it takes to sustain and grow this success: stronger cybersecurity, enhanced safety measures, and the resources to meet the demands of modern classrooms.

That‚Äôs exactly what I‚Äôm working to deliver‚Äîthrough increased federal funding, targeted support, and bipartisan legislation like the Measures for Safer School Districts Act, because protecting our kids and supporting our educators is not optional‚Äîit‚Äôs a national priority.

Thank you to Dr. Bridget O‚ÄôConnell, Rich Heffernan, Amber Schlosser, Donna Holmes, Silvia LeBlanc, and the entire Palisades team for your vision, dedication, and leadership. You‚Äôre not just preparing students for the future‚Äîyou‚Äôre helping shape it.
